		<h2>By Zachary Green</h2>

		<div class="image-container">
			
			<p class="film-content">
						
<em>The Lost Weekend</em> portrays an unrelenting theme of alcoholism and addiction displayed through Don Birnam. Alcoholism plays a huge part in Don’s life and relationship, albeit not a good one. Such issues were largely overlooked in Hollywood at the time so the movie was a very grim portrayal. Wilder illustrates how alcoholism consumes Don, and all over a single weekend of booze filled activities. The film is very realistic, even more so because it is an older film with not very many dramatic effects.  Don experiences significant collateral damage because of his addiction. More specifically, his friends and the relationship with his family members deteriorates because of this. Wilder's illustration of Don’s illness will stay relevant 1000 years from now, given alcohol will always be around and unfortunately there will always be people struggling with the illness. Given the nature of the film and the time period it was produced in, it offers a very realistic view of the struggles he faces and as such could always be a good film to teach people about the dangers of alcohol. 
</p>
